                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                            Barbital (or, if you prefer, its slightly more archaic cousin, barbitone), was initially released under the brand name Veronal for the pure acid form, and later as Medinal for its soluble sodium salt. It holds the somewhat dubious distinction of being the first commercially available [barbiturate](/Barbiturate). For a period from 1903 until the mid-1950s, it served as a popular solution for the nightly struggle against wakefulness, functioning as a [sleeping aid](/Hypnotic). The more formal chemical nomenclature for this compound includes diethylmalonyl urea or diethylbarbituric acid, which logically leads to its sodium salt being recognized as sodium diethylbarbiturate.

## Synthesis

The origin story of [Barbital](/Barbital), initially known by its rather poetic trade name "Veronal," traces back to 1902. It was in that year that the illustrious German chemists, [Emil Fischer](/Hermann_Emil_Fischer) and [Joseph von Mering](/Joseph_von_Mering), successfully synthesized this compound. Their groundbreaking findings were subsequently unveiled to the scientific community in 1903, marking a significant milestone in pharmaceutical chemistry.

The primary method for preparing [Barbital](/Barbital) involved a [condensation reaction](/Condensation_reaction). This process entailed combining [diethylmalonic ester](/Diethyl_malonate) with [urea](/Urea) in the discernible presence of [sodium ethoxide](/Sodium_ethoxide). Alternatively, one could achieve its synthesis by introducing a minimum of two molar equivalents of [ethyl iodide](/Ethyl_iodide) to either the silver salt of [malonylurea (barbituric acid)](/Barbituric_acid) or, more practically, to a basic solution of the acid itself. The culmination of these precise chemical maneuvers yielded an odorless, slightly bitter substance, presenting as a white crystalline powder. Not exactly a feast for the senses, but then, most things that mess with your brain aren't.

This introduction of [Barbital](/Barbital) was the direct consequence of Fischer and von Mering's meticulous investigations into the pharmacological characteristics of various open and closed [acylureas](/Acylurea), which at the time were broadly categorized as ureides. Operating under the hypothesis that a significant portion of a compound's [hypnotic](/Hypnotic) efficacy was intrinsically linked to the presence of [ethyl groups](/Ethyl_group) within its molecular structure, they systematically prepared several related compounds. These included diethylacetyl urea, diethylmalonyl urea (which is, as you've no doubt gathered, [Barbital](/Barbital) itself), and [dipropylmalonyl urea](/Propylbarbital).

Their comparative studies revealed intriguing results regarding their sedative potentials. Diethylacetyl urea was found to possess a potency roughly equivalent to [sulphonal](/Sulfonmethane), a sedative already established in medical practice at the time. The third compound, [dipropylmalonyl urea](/Propylbarbital), proved to be remarkably potent, boasting an efficacy four times greater than [Barbital](/Barbital). However, its use was plagued by undesirable and protracted after-effects, rendering it less suitable for widespread clinical application. [Barbital](/Barbital), in this carefully calibrated spectrum, occupied a middle ground, offering a balance of effectiveness and tolerable side effects, making it a more viable candidate for therapeutic use. A compromise, as ever, is what humanity settles for.

The synthesis of [Barbital](/Barbital) can also be elegantly achieved through a [condensation reaction](/Condensation_reaction) between [urea](/Urea) and [diethyl-2,2-diethylmalonate](/Diethyl-2,2-diethylmalonate), which is itself a derivative of [diethyl malonate](/Diethyl_malonate). This alternative pathway further underscores the foundational chemical principles employed in its creation.

